      "source": [
        "#| echo: false\n",
        "#| include: false\n",
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "#| label: fig-residual-plot-build\n",
        "residual_plot_output_path = CACHE_PATHS[\"report_exports\"] / \"plots\" / \"section4_residual_plot_inline.png\"\n",
        "residual_plot_output_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "if not (use_section4_exports and residual_plot_output_path.exists()):\n",
        "    # Residuals: all participants on one plot + per-participant trend line\n",
        "    plot_source = residual_plot_fit_source\n",
        "\n",
        "# Color-blind friendly palette (Okabe–Ito)\n",
        "palette = [\n",
        "    \"#0072B2\",  # blue\n",
        "    \"#D55E00\",  # vermillion\n",
        "    \"#009E73\",  # bluish green\n",
        "    \"#CC79A7\",  # reddish purple\n",
        "    \"#E69F00\",  # orange\n",
        "    \"#56B4E9\",  # sky blue\n",
        "    \"#F0E442\",  # yellow (use sparingly on white)\n",
        "    \"#000000\",  # black\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.style.use(\"seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid\")\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5.1, 3.6))\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.axhline(0.0, color=\"#4a5568\", linewidth=1.2, linestyle=\"--\")\n",
        "\n",
        "for i, r in enumerate(results):\n",
        "    color = palette[i % len(palette)]\n",
        "    run = select_run(r, plot_source)\n",
        "\n",
        "    df = run.reward_frame.copy()\n",
        "    df = df.loc[df[\"complete_window\"]].copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "    x = (24 - pd.to_numeric(df[\"fitbit_observed_hours\"], errors=\"coerce\").fillna(0.0)).round().clip(0, 24)\n",
        "    y = pd.to_numeric(df[\"latent_reward_24h\"], errors=\"coerce\") - pd.to_numeric(df[\"fitbit_observed_reward_24h\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    plot_df = pd.DataFrame({\"x\": x, \"y\": y}).dropna()\n",
        "    plot_df[\"x\"] = plot_df[\"x\"].astype(int)\n",
        "\n",
        "    ax.scatter(\n",
        "        plot_df[\"x\"],\n",
        "        plot_df[\"y\"],\n",
        "        color=color,\n",
        "        alpha=0.75,\n",
        "        s=28,\n",
        "        edgecolor=\"white\",\n",
        "        linewidth=0.5,\n",
        "        label=r.participant_id,\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "    if len(plot_df) >= 2 and plot_df[\"x\"].nunique() >= 2:\n",
        "        b, a = np.polyfit(plot_df[\"x\"].to_numpy(dtype=float), plot_df[\"y\"].to_numpy(dtype=float), deg=1)\n",
        "        xs = np.linspace(0, 24, 200)\n",
        "        ys = a + b * xs\n",
        "        ax.plot(xs, ys, color=color, linewidth=1.6, alpha=0.95)\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_title(\"Filtered reward residual vs missingness\", fontsize=11)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel(\"Missing Fitbit hours in 24-hour window\", fontsize=10)\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel(\"Filtered reward − observed subtotal\", fontsize=10)\n",
        "ax.set_xlim(-0.5, 24.5)\n",
        "ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0, 25, 2))\n",
        "ax.tick_params(axis=\"both\", labelsize=9)\n",
        "ax.legend(frameon=False, ncol=1, fontsize=8)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.savefig(residual_plot_output_path, dpi=180, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n",
        "plt.close(fig)"
      ],
      "id": "fig-residual-plot-build",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "```{=latex}\n",
        "\\noindent\n",
        "\\begin{minipage}[t]{0.56\\textwidth}\n",
        "\\vspace{0pt}\n",
        "\\centering\n",
        "\\includegraphics[width=\\linewidth]{cache/computedraft/v1/rl2_masked_v4/report_exports/plots/section4_residual_plot_inline.png}\n",
        "\\captionof{figure}{Filtered reward residual versus missingness for the three participant demonstrations.}\n",
        "\\label{fig-residual-plot}\n",
        "\\end{minipage}\\hfill\n",
        "\\begin{minipage}[t]{0.40\\textwidth}\n",
        "\\vspace{0pt}\n",
        "Figure \\ref{fig-residual-plot} shows a linear trend in how much the estimated latent exceeds the observed. This is unsurprising; if the observed only sums 8 non-zero buckets, the latent sums 24 non-zero buckets, and might be approximately three times larger. This discrepancy is why we use a latent model in the first place, as we expect that there are many steps the participant is taking that are not being picked up by Fitbit or other measurement devices. This phenomenon presents challenges with finding a representative benchmark that we discuss below.\n",
        "\\end{minipage}\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "# Benchmarks for Aggregate Modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "There were several benchmarks to consider, and narrowing them down was challenging. Since our goal was prediction rather than inference, we prioritized models that perform best on unseen data. Specifically, we aimed to improve the accuracy of predicted 24-hour rewards when users have missing hourly observations. Because we fit 78 personalized models jointly, we also need aggregate summaries that capture predictive ability across participants.\n",
        "\n",
        "Direct error is only meaningful on hours where Fitbit originally recorded nonzero step counts. When a participant is not wearing the device, the observed series can contain zeros that do not represent true inactivity, so evaluating prediction error against those zeros would be misleading. We therefore use a masking approach: for each participant, we refit the model after masking 20% of the observed hourly Fitbit data and then evaluate reconstruction quality on the held-out masked observations. We report both hourly reconstruction metrics and a daily held-out subtotal benchmark that aligns more directly with the 24-hour reward target. Additional details on the masked subtotal metric are given in the supplementary material.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Inference Settings\n",
        "\n",
        "We ran a global IF2 MLE search for each of the three models with two stages. Stage 1, 32 starts, 1024 particles, 16 iterations, with 256 evaluation particles with 16 evaluation repeats, with a smaller stage 2, 16 starts, 512 particles, 16 iterations, 256 evaluation particles repeated 8 times. Each fit took about an hour and a half on a 3080 Nvidia GPU with 10GB of VRAM, with 8704 CUDA cores.\n",
        "\n",
        "The scale of this made computation very challenging! Considering just the version with no pooling, each of the 78 participants had 3 parameters, which comes out to 234 parameters total. Running this across 3 models was very time intensive, and getting it to function correctly in qmd was another challenge entirely! \n",
        "\n",
        "In Table~\\ref{tbl-inference-search-window} we display the window for each global model that we perform the search on. $k$ was searched on a log scale, and for the partial pooling, the variance $\\tau$ and $\\mu$ for the penalty term were searched also on the log scale. Figure~\\ref{fig-empirical-mu-logk-window} displays the global window for those distribution terms, alongside empirical bootstrap estimates from the partial-pooling and no-pooling models. It is not conclusive, but it suggests that our window does cover this region."
      ],
      "id": "dca65cd4"
    },
